  {
      "id": "asthma",
      "name": "Asthma",
      "category": "Chest & Breathing",
      "emotionalRoot": "A pattern of smothered voice, unprocessed grief, fear, and a body that may feel unsafe taking up air, space, or need.",
      "metaphor": "Your lungs are an underfunded tech-support call center where every dust bunny gets flagged as biological warfare and the phone lines clamp shut.",
      "physiologicalDescription": "Asthma involves airway inflammation, bronchial smooth muscle constriction, mucus production, air trapping, and a panic-feedback loop that can worsen the breathing experience.",
      "sarcasticAdvice": "You do not only have a lung problem. You may also have a swallowed-speech problem, a grief problem, and a nervous system that learned to make itself smaller instead of asking for space.",
      "physicalTherapyTip": "Keep your prescribed rescue inhaler available and use it exactly as directed. For mild, stable stress-related tightness only, sit upright, inhale gently for 4 seconds, and exhale for 6 seconds through the nose or pursed lips. Stop if symptoms worsen.",
      "mindfulnessPrompts": [
          "Where in my life do I feel emotionally smothered, controlled, or unable to breathe as myself?",
          "What sentence, boundary, grief, or need have I been swallowing instead of expressing?",
          "Who taught me that needing air, space, help, or comfort was inconvenient?",
          "What would change if I let my exhale be longer than my fear?"
      ],
      "structuredContent": {
          "version": 1,
          "hero": {
              "primaryPattern": "Airway inflammation, bronchospasm, mucus load, air trapping, and panic feedback may amplify this symptom.",
              "cascade": [
                  "Trigger Recognition",
                  "Immune Alarm",
                  "Bronchospasm",
                  "Mucus Load",
                  "Air Trapping",
                  "Panic Feedback Loop"
              ],
              "tags": [
                  "#airway check",
                  "#rescue plan",
                  "#unspoken grief"
              ],
              "safetyPreview": "Severe shortness of breath, blue lips or fingernails, trouble speaking, chest pain, fainting, confusion, or rescue inhaler not helping require urgent medical attention."
          },
          "biologyPathway": [
              {
                  "title": "Trigger Recognition",
                  "short": "Trigger hits sensitive airways.",
                  "detail": "Allergens, cold air, exertion, smoke, infection, laughter, or stress can activate an already sensitive airway system. The trigger may be physical, environmental, infectious, or stress-amplified. The point is not that it is imaginary. The point is that the airway threshold is low and primed to react."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Immune Alarm",
                  "short": "Inflammatory alarm activates.",
                  "detail": "Mast cells and inflammatory pathways release mediators such as histamine and leukotrienes. The airway lining becomes irritated, swollen, and reactive, which makes the bronchial tubes more sensitive to the next trigger."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Bronchospasm",
                  "short": "Bronchial muscle tightens.",
                  "detail": "Smooth muscle around the bronchial tubes contracts. The airway narrows, airflow becomes turbulent, and wheezing may appear. This is airway smooth muscle tightening around the breathing tubes, not a bone or joint problem."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Mucus Load",
                  "short": "Mucus adds resistance.",
                  "detail": "The airway produces thicker mucus. This adds resistance, increases coughing, and can make the chest feel clogged or heavy, like air is moving through a narrow wet straw."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Air Trapping",
                  "short": "Air gets trapped.",
                  "detail": "Air may enter more easily than it leaves. Asthma often feels like you cannot get air in, but a major part of the problem can be getting air out. The lungs struggle to empty, creating pressure, tightness, and the sense that the next breath has nowhere to go."
              },
              {
                  "title": "Panic Feedback Loop",
                  "short": "Panic tightens the loop.",
                  "detail": "The sensation of restricted breathing alarms the nervous system. Alarm increases effort, tension, and sympathetic arousal, which can worsen the breathing experience. Rescue medication and medical care matter first; nervous-system calming is support, not a replacement."
              }
          ],
          "interpretations": {
              "clinical": {
                  "label": "Strictly Serious",
                  "title": "The Deep Translation",
                  "sections": [
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 1 — Lung-Kidney Root Imbalance",
                          "body": [
                              "In Traditional Chinese Medicine, the Lung governs Qi and Wei Qi: the protective boundary between self and world. The Lung descends and disperses. It takes in the new through inhale and releases the old through exhale.",
                              "Emotionally, the Lung is associated with grief: losses never mourned, tears never shed, and goodbyes never fully said. When grief stays unexpressed, the Lung's descending function can be symbolically imagined as blocked or flooded.",
                              "The Kidney, which is said to grasp Qi for deeper breathing, is linked with fear. The result is a body caught between grief and terror: aggressive inhale, restricted exhale, and a nervous system that does not trust the next breath."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 2 — The Smothered Voice Archetype",
                          "body": [
                              "Asthma can symbolically mirror the suppressed Righteous Voice: the part that knows how to say, 'I'm suffocating here.' Somewhere along the line, speaking up, crying out, needing help, or saying no may have felt punished, ignored, or inconvenient.",
                              "The airway becomes the metaphor: expression feels dangerous, so the body contracts around breath. Every wheeze becomes a symbolic unsaid sentence. Every tight-chested moment becomes a backlog of no, stop, listen, and I need help."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 3 — Generational Grief Template",
                          "body": [
                              "Families carry unprocessed losses: deaths, migrations, poverty, war, abandonment, silence, and grief nobody had time or permission to feel.",
                              "In a mind-body framework, that inherited pattern can look like a diaphragm that braces, an immune system that overreacts, and a chest that prepares for danger before danger actually arrives."
                          ]
                      },
                      {
                          "heading": "Stage 4 — Clinical Cascade",
                          "body": [
                              "Medically, asthma involves airway inflammation, bronchial smooth muscle constriction, mucus production, and air trapping.",
                              "Stress can worsen symptoms by increasing autonomic arousal, inflammatory signaling, and panic feedback. Bronchospasm narrows the airway. Mucus adds resistance. Air gets in but struggles to get out. CO2 rises. Panic rises. Panic tightens the loop."
                          ]
                      }
                  ]
              },
              "witty": {
                  "label": "Comedic & Witty",
                  "title": "The Underfunded Lung Tech-Support Center",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "Your lungs are an overworked, underfunded tech-support call center in a damp basement. There is a broken printer in the corner that has been beeping ERROR since 2018. The hold music is one haunted flute note. Every time a customer calls, the system panics and hangs up.",
                      "Your bronchial tubes are the phone lines. Normally, calls go through. Air moves in and out without a board meeting. But your nervous system, the exhausted IT manager, installed a security update that now flags everything as a threat.",
                      "Pollen? Threat. Cold air? Threat. Laughing too hard? Emergency protocol. A dust bunny in the next county? Biological warfare, apparently.",
                      "Then the automatic hang-up protocol kicks in. The bronchioles clamp shut like a fist. The mucus department, overworked since the 90s, floods the lines with sticky nonsense. The air you inhaled gets trapped because the exit doors slammed shut before it could leave.",
                      "Somewhere on the wall is a motivational poster that used to say KEEP CALM AND CARRY ON, but someone crossed out CARRY ON and wrote CLENCH in marker. The coffee mug says WORLD'S OKAYEST BREATHER. The automated system is running the whole building now, and the automated system is terrified of everything."
                  ]
              },
              "brutal": {
                  "label": "Brutally Honest",
                  "title": "The Swallowed Voice Reality Check",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "You do not only have a lung problem. You may also have an 'I'll just swallow this' problem. A 'no one wants to hear me anyway' problem. A 'crying is weak' problem. A 'if I keep shrinking myself, maybe nobody will get mad' problem.",
                      "Every time you wanted to say 'I'm drowning here' and swallowed it, your body took notes. Every time you bit back tears because no one was listening anyway, your chest learned the lesson. Every time you smiled through a room full of people ignoring your needs, your system rehearsed contraction.",
                      "The wheeze can become the unsaid sentence trying to escape through a pinhole. The tight chest can become grief with nowhere to go except smooth muscle spasm and panic.",
                      "And yes, keep the inhaler. The inhaler matters. The inhaler can save your life. But the inhaler does not say the thing you refused to say. It does not cry the grief you stored. It does not set the boundary. It opens airways; it does not open the locked room where your voice has been sitting in the dark.",
                      "The work is not pretending asthma is 'just emotional.' That would be stupid, and frankly we have enough stupidity stocked for the winter. The work is taking the medical reality seriously while also asking why your nervous system is so prepared to suffocate quietly.",
                      "Learn to ask for help before your body has to scream it. Learn to say no before your chest says it for you. Learn to take up air. Learn to take up space. Armor down, or stay breathless in every way except the one your inhaler can temporarily fix."
                  ]
              }
          },
          "influenceLayers": [
              {
                  "layer": 1,
                  "title": "Medical Reality",
                  "tag": "Anatomical",
                  "paragraphs": [
                      "Asthma is a real airway condition involving inflammation, bronchospasm, mucus, and air trapping.",
